content.solution:
**(a)** $a = 1$, $b = \sqrt{3}$ (first quadrant)
$$\begin{aligned}
 |z_1| &= \sqrt{1 + 3} = 2 \\
 \theta &= \arctan\frac{\sqrt{3}}{1} = \frac{\pi}{3}
\end{aligned}$$

**(b)** $a = -2$, $b = -2$ (third quadrant)
$$\begin{aligned}
 |z_2| &= \sqrt{4 + 4} = 2\sqrt{2} \\
 \text{Reference: } &\arctan\frac{2}{2} = \frac{\pi}{4} \\
 \theta &= \pi + \frac{\pi}{4} = \frac{5\pi}{4} \quad \text{(or } -\frac{3\pi}{4}\text{)}
\end{aligned}$$

**(c)** $z_3 = -5$ is on the negative real axis
$$\begin{aligned}
 |z_3| &= 5 \\
 \theta &= \pi
\end{aligned}$$

content.content:
When finding the argument, always consider the quadrant! The arctangent 
function only returns values in $\left(-\frac{\pi}{2}, \frac{\pi}{2}\right)$, 
so you must adjust for quadrants II, III, and IV.
